<p>Here's the thing about SEO that nobody in this industry wants to tell you: <strong>most of what you've been sold is useless.</strong></p>

<p>Not because SEO doesn't work. It does. It's one of the most powerful tools a local service business can use. But the version of SEO you've been paying for? The monthly reports with graphs that go up and to the right while your phone stays silent? That's not SEO. That's a screensaver.</p>

<h2 id="the-problem">The Problem With "Safe" SEO</h2>

<p>Most agencies sell you what I call "checkbox SEO." They optimize your title tags. They add some keywords to your homepage. They write a blog post nobody reads. They send you a report.</p>

<p>Then they do it again next month. And the month after that. And you keep paying because the report looks professional and you don't know enough to argue with it.</p>

<p>Meanwhile, your competitor — the one who started six months after you — is ranking above you in Maps. He's getting the calls. He's booking the jobs. And you're staring at a PDF wondering what went wrong.</p>

<blockquote>
<p>"The best SEO strategy is the one that treats your website like a salesperson, not a filing cabinet."</p>
</blockquote>

<h2 id="what-actually-works">What Actually Works for Local Service Businesses</h2>

<p>Here's what moves the needle for contractors, plumbers, roofers, and every other service business that depends on local customers:</p>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Google Business Profile optimization</strong> — Not just filling in the blanks. Posting regularly, getting reviews systematically, and responding to every single one.</li>
    <li><strong>Service-area pages that rank</strong> — "Plumber in [city]" pages that actually say something useful, not keyword-stuffed garbage.</li>
    <li><strong>Review velocity</strong> — Getting more reviews than your competitors, consistently, every week. Not in bursts. Not when you remember.</li>
    <li><strong>Technical foundation</strong> — Fast site. Mobile-first. Schema markup. The stuff that lets Google trust you.</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="the-review-game">The Review Game Nobody Is Playing Right</h2>

<p>Let me tell you about reviews, because this is where most businesses are leaving money on the table.</p>

<p>Your competitor has 47 reviews. You have 12. Google sees that and makes a very simple decision about who to show first. It's not complicated. It's not about keywords. It's about trust signals.</p>

<p>The fix isn't hard, but it has to be systematic:</p>

<ol>
    <li><strong>Ask every customer.</strong> Not some. Not the happy ones. Every single one.</li>
    <li><strong>Make it brain-dead simple.</strong> Text them a link. One tap to leave a review. Done.</li>
    <li><strong>Respond to every review.</strong> Good or bad. This shows Google (and potential customers) that you're paying attention.</li>
    <li><strong>Never stop.</strong> The moment you stop asking is the moment your competitor overtakes you.</li>
</ol>

<div class="callout">
    <p class="callout-title">⚡ The Badmouth Take</p>
    <p>Reviews aren't a marketing tactic. They're the closest thing to a cheat code that exists in local SEO. If you're not systematically generating them, you're playing the game with one hand tied behind your back.</p>
</div>

<h2 id="content-that-ranks">Content That Ranks vs. Content That Exists</h2>

<p>There's a difference between having content on your website and having content that does something.</p>

<p>A blog post titled "5 Tips for Maintaining Your HVAC System" isn't going to rank. It's been written ten thousand times. Google has no reason to show yours.</p>

<p>But a page titled "HVAC Repair in Mesa, AZ — What to Do When Your AC Dies at 2AM" with real information, real pricing context, and a clear call to action? That's a page that can rank, convert, and make you money.</p>

<p><strong>The difference is intent.</strong> One is content for content's sake. The other is content for your customer's sake.</p>

<h2 id="the-fix">The Fix: Stop Chasing, Start Building</h2>

<p>Here's the strategy in plain English:</p>

<ul>
    <li><strong>Fix your Google Business Profile first.</strong> It's free and it's the fastest way to show up in Maps.</li>
    <li><strong>Build service pages that match what people search for.</strong> "Roof repair in [city]," not "Our services."</li>
    <li><strong>Systematize your reviews.</strong> Automate the ask. Make it part of your process.</li>
    <li><strong>Stop paying for monthly SEO reports that don't move the needle.</strong> If your phone isn't ringing more, something's wrong.</li>
</ul>

<p>SEO isn't magic. It's not even that complicated. But it does require doing the right things in the right order. And that's what most agencies get wrong — they start with the fancy stuff and skip the fundamentals.</p>

<p><strong>Fix the foundation. Then build on it. That's the whole strategy.</strong></p>

